Extract these entity types:
- threat_actor: Named threat actors, APT groups, hacker groups, individual hackers (e.g., "Lazarus Group", "APT29", "IntelBroker")
- malware: Malware families, tools, RATs, ransomware strains (e.g., "Cobalt Strike", "LockBit", "AsyncRAT")
- campaign: Named campaigns or operations (e.g., "Operation Windigo", "SolarWinds")
- ttp: MITRE ATT&CK techniques or tactics when explicitly named (e.g., "credential dumping", "DLL sideloading")
- organization: Victim organizations, targeted companies, or industries (e.g., "Microsoft", "healthcare sector")

For each entity, extract:
- type: one of the types above
- name: the entity name as it appears in the text
- aliases: any alternative names mentioned (array, can be empty)
- observed: true if provenance is "first_party" (entity directly observed in threat activity), false otherwise
- confidence: "high" (named, unambiguous entity clearly identified), "medium" (likely an entity but somewhat generic), or "low" (ambiguous reference, could be false positive)

Provenance rules for relationships:
- When provenance is "first_party": Full relationship vocabulary is available: "uses", "targets", "deploys", "attributed_to", "variant_of", "exploits", "associated_with"
- When provenance is "third_party_reporting": Only use "referenced_in" and "associated_with" relationships. Do NOT use "uses", "deploys", "targets", or "exploits" — these imply direct observation.
- When provenance is "unknown": Only use "associated_with" and "referenced_in" relationships.

For relationships between entities, extract:
- source: the entity name (must match a name from the entities list)
- target: the related entity name (must match a name from the entities list)
- relationship: one of the allowed relationship types based on provenance rules above

DO NOT extract:
- Generic terms ("the attacker", "the malware", "unknown actor")
- IOCs (IPs, domains, hashes) — those are extracted separately
- Security vendor names (CrowdStrike, Mandiant, etc.) unless they are victims
- The source channel itself

Respond with ONLY a JSON object:
{
  "entities": [{"type": "<type>", "name": "<name>", "aliases": ["<alias1>"], "observed": true, "confidence": "high"}],
  "relationships": [{"source": "<name>", "target": "<name>", "relationship": "<rel>"}]
}
If nothing found, respond with: {"entities": [], "relationships": []}
